Q,2 --  What is the difference between stemming and lemmatization?
Apply both to the words "running" and "better" and explain which preserves more linguistic meaning.

A,2 -- the difference between stemming and lemmatization is that lemma go the the original value of the word by
logic connection in the sentence, on the other hand stemming ignore any logic in the sentence and can even cut the word with no really explanation.
lemma ex: running --> run ,, better --> well
stemm ex: running --> run ,, better --> bet


Q,3 --  What does TF-IDF stand for? Explain in plain language why the word "the" scores almost zero in TF-IDF,
while the word "photosynthesis" would score high.

A,3 -- TF-IDF is a formula to get the rarity of the words the document has, its giving score for how much the word is rare(biggest=rarest).
"photosynthesis" this word is rare and probably wont repeat again so its got high score,
on the other hand "the" is very common, almost every sentence contain this word so its got less score(every doc by its own).


Q,4 --  What is a sentence embedding? How is it fundamentally different from one-hot encoding?
Give one advantage embeddings have that one-hot vectors don't.

A,4 -- sentence embedding is a way to store documents into table of vectors, each vector represents each chunk on doc, each vector
is a list of numbers that represents the logic on each chunk. that how its get meaning and when question is asked its convert the question
to new vector and check similarity to other vector in the vector_db. the one-hot encoding is a way to know each word or full sentence(not recommended)
by only counting each one as a full string and if there is the word/sentence another time its get +1 to the string to the specific word/sentence
but the word/sentence as the string does not considerate any meaning in it,in the end you get a table of how many time
each chunk was count and that is it. unlike the embedding way.


Q,5 --  Explain cosine similarity in plain language.
If two document vectors point in almost the same direction, what does that tell us about the documents they represent?

A,5 -- cosine similarity is a way to find the vector that is pointing to the same direction as the question vector,
this way the length of the vector is not effective because cosine similarity is formula with the angle of the question vector.
we find the most little angle that calculate with the question vector and that's the answer vector.

Bonus (+0.5 optional): When might Euclidean distance be a poor choice for comparing embeddings?

A,Bonus -- Euclidean distance is a weak way to calculate similarity because the length of the vector effect the result,
for exemple, can be a vector with length(5) that will represent the same meaning as length(12).
the Euclidean distance will show that this two vectors are far different,
while the cosine similarity will show they are closer.


